DSCI 352 Report Out 3

Anthony Brennan
December 5, 2019

Recap: Question

  • Question
    • Can I predict an expected goals scored, goal differential, and win probabilities for various European soccer matches using player data from FIFA video games?

Recap: Datasets

  • 4 Datasets from Kaggle: Game data, player data from Fifa 17, 18, & 19
    • Applying Fifa 17 to 2016-17 season, Fifa 18 to 2017-18 season, and Fifa 19 to 2018-19 season
  • Data for 17 leagues
    • England (1st-4th divisions)
    • Germany, France, Italy, Spain (1st-2nd divisions)
    • Belgium, Netherlands, Portugal, Scotland, Turkey (1st division)
  • Total of 19314 games
  • 334 teams and ~9500 players for each of the 3 years

Models

  • Predicting goal differential
    • Created 2 different models using regression and svm models
  • Predicting goals scored using
    • Created 2 different models using regression and svm models
  • Win probabilities
    • 1st method use t-score probabilities on the predicted goal differential
    • 2nd method use poisson distributions on each team's predict goals scored

Regression Model

  • lm(GoalDiff ~ HomeAttacking + AwayAttacking + HomeMidfield + AwayMidfield + HomeDefense + AwayDefense + HomeBench + AwayBench, training)

SVM Model

  • svm(GoalDiff ~ HomeAttacking + AwayAttacking + HomeMidfield + AwayMidfield + HomeDefense + AwayDefense + HomeBench + AwayBench, data = training, kernel = “linear”, cost = 10, scale = FALSE)

Modeling Method 2 - Poisson

Regression Model

  • Home Goals Scored
    • lm(FTHG ~ HomeOverall + AwayOverall + HomeAttacking + AwayDefense + AwayGoalkeeper, training)
  • Away Goals Scored
    • lm(FTAG ~ HomeOverall + AwayOverall + AwayAttacking + HomeDefense + HomeGoalkeeper, training)

SVM Model

  • Home Goals Scored
    • svm(FTHG ~ HomeOverall + AwayOverall + HomeAttacking + AwayDefense + AwayGoalkeeper, data = training, kernel = “linear”, cost = 10, scale = FALSE)
  • Away Goals Scored
    • svm(FTAG ~ HomeOverall + AwayOverall + AwayAttacking + HomeDefense + HomeGoalkeeper, data = training, kernel = “linear”, cost = 10, scale = FALSE)
